---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
import SoftmaxInspector from '../../components/interactive/SoftmaxInspector';
---

<BaseLayout title="Softmax Turns Scores into a Distribution">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L12" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does softmax change?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        Logits are raw scores — they can be any number. To choose the next token, we need <strong>probabilities</strong>: positive numbers that sum to 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Softmax</strong> converts logits to probabilities. It exponentiates each logit (making them all positive), then divides by the total. The result: the largest logit gets the biggest probability, and all probabilities sum to exactly 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        The exponential function amplifies differences. A logit that is just slightly larger than the rest can dominate after softmax. This is why softmax makes the model's top choice stand out sharply.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Interactive — Softmax Inspector</div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
        Adjust the logits and temperature. Watch how the probability distribution changes. Lower temperature makes the distribution sharper. Higher temperature makes it more uniform.
      </p>
      <SoftmaxInspector client:load />
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Softmax of [2.0, 1.0, 0.1]:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div>exp(2.0) = 7.39 &nbsp;&nbsp; exp(1.0) = 2.72 &nbsp;&nbsp; exp(0.1) = 1.11</div>
          <div style="margin-top: 4px;">sum = 7.39 + 2.72 + 1.11 = 11.22</div>
          <div style="margin-top: 8px; color: var(--sem-logits);">
            probs = [7.39/11.22, 2.72/11.22, 1.11/11.22] = [0.659, 0.242, 0.099]
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          All positive. Sum to 1.000. The largest logit (2.0) gets 65.9% of the probability.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Input logits: [|V|]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-logits);">Output probabilities: [|V|] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">same shape, but now all positive and sum to 1</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-logits);">p&#x1D62; = exp(z&#x1D62;) / &sum;&#x2C7C; exp(z&#x2C7C;)</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Every p&#x1D62; &gt; 0, and &sum; p&#x1D62; = 1</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Softmax converts logits to probabilities. You have seen it here at the output head. Later, you will see it used again inside the model's layers. In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the <code>ggml_soft_max</code> operation handles this.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Softmax itself is cheap — it is elementwise exp plus a sum. But the exponentiation can cause numerical issues with very large logits. Real implementations subtract the max logit first for numerical stability. This is a detail you will see in code.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L12"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L12-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'After softmax, can any probability be negative?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Yes, if the logit was negative', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'No, exp(x) is always positive', isCorrect: true },
            ],
            explanation: 'The exponential function always produces positive numbers, so every softmax output is positive regardless of the input logit.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L12-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'If one logit is much larger than the rest, what happens after softmax?',
            tag: 'math',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'All probabilities become roughly equal', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'The largest logit gets most of the probability mass', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Softmax outputs stay the same as the logits', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'Exponentials amplify differences. A much larger logit dominates the sum, capturing most of the probability. This is why models can be confident.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
